claims:
Claims CLAIMS  What Is Claimed is: 1. A method of characterizing the effective spatial resolution of a video segment comprising acquiring a baseband video; storing at least two images of said baseband video; calculating a log magnitude spectrum for each of the stored at least two images of the baseband video; combining the log magnitude spectrum for each of the stored at least two imaged of the baseband video to form an average log magnitude spectrum; and applying prescribed thresholds to the log magnitude spectrum to form a signature contour of the stored images. 2. The method of claim 1 further comprising the step of storing the signature contour of the stored images. 3. The method of claim 1 further comprising the step of generating a parametric representation of the signature contour; and storing the parametric representation in a data base. 4. The method of claim 1 further comprising the steps of: acquiring a second baseband video based on successive downscaling and upscaling of said baseband video; storing at least two second images of said second baseband video; 

 calculating a second log magnitude spectrum for each of the stored at least two second images of the second baseband video; combining the second log magnitude spectrum for each of the stored at least two second imaged of the second baseband video to form a second average log magnitude spectrum; and applying prescribed thresholds to the second log magnitude spectrum to form a second signature contour of the second stored images; comparing the size of the contours of the signature contour and the second signature contour; determining a sensitivity of contour size based on downscaling; and recording a value of the sensitivity. 5. The method of claim 4 further comprising the steps of: evaluating the effective spatial resolution of the first signature contour and the second signature contour; and selecting a baseband video that has maximum effective resolution at a prescribed bitrate 6. The method of claim 5 wherein the maximum effective resolution is less than or equal to a native resolution of an identified display. 7. The method of claim 5 wherein the maximum effective resolution is less than or equal to a native resolution of an identified transcoder. 8. The method of claim 4 further comprising the step of: 

 generating a compressed version of a baseband video wherein a compression is based, at least in part, on one of the signature contour and the second signature contour. 9. A system of monitoring the performance of a transmission system, comprising selecting a reference signature contour map for a signal; determining an actual signature contour map for a transmitted version of the signal; comparing the reference signature contour map information and the actual signature contour map information; and generating an alert if the signature reference contour map information and the actual signature contour map information differ by more than a predetermined value. 10. The system of claim 9 wherein: the actual signature contour map information is a parametric representation of the actual signature contour map; and the reference signature contour map information is a parametric representation of the references signature contour map. 11. The system of claim 10 wherein: the parametric representation of the reference signature contour map information is a diameter of a maximum contour of the reference signature contour map; and the parametric representation of the actual signature contour map information is a diameter of a maximum contour of the actual signature contour map. 12. A method for characterizing segments of a video, comprising: acquiring a first picture from a video signal; calculating a first spatial frequency transform of the first picture; fitting a first line to the log magnitude of a main horizontal component of the first spatial frequency transform; storing at least one of a first slope, a first intercept, and a first correlation coefficient of the first line; acquiring a second picture from a video signal; calculating a second spatial frequency transform of the second picture; fitting a second line to the log magnitude of main horizontal component of the second spatial frequency transform; storing at least one of a second slope, a second intercept, and a second correlation coefficient of the second line; determining a first difference between at least one of the first slope and the second slope, the first intercept and the second intercept and the first correlation coefficient and the second correlation coefficient; determining whether the first difference exceeds a first prescribed threshold; and signaling that the first prescribed threshold has been exceeded. 13. The method of claim 12 further comprising the steps of: fitting a third line to the log magnitude of a main vertical component of the first spatial frequency transform; 

 storing at least one of a third slope, a third intercept, and a third correlation coefficient of the third line; fitting a fourth line to the log magnitude of a main vertical component of the second spatial frequency transform; storing at least one of a fourth slope, a fourth intercept, and a fourth correlation coefficient of the fourth line; determining a second difference between at least one of the third slope and the fourth slope, the third intercept and the fourth intercept and the third correlation coefficient and the fourth correlation coefficient; determining whether the second difference exceeds a second prescribed threshold; and signaling that the second prescribed threshold has been exceeded. 14. The method of claim 13 wherein at least one of the first line, the second line, the third line and the fourth line is fitted using linear regression. 15. The method of claim 12 further comprising the steps of: comparing at least one of the first slope, the second slope, the first intercept, the second intercept, the first correlation coefficient and the second correlation coefficient to a threshold; and generating a segment-boundary indicator when the threshold is exceeded be a prescribed quantity. 16. The method of claim 12 further comprising the steps of: 

 comparing at least one of the first slope, the second slope, the first intercept, the second intercept, the first correlation coefficient and the second correlation coefficient to a threshold; and generating a segment-boundary indicator when the threshold is exceeded be a prescribed percentage. 17. The method of claim 12 further comprising the steps of: storing the first difference; transmitting the difference when the difference exceeds a prescribed threshold; and recording the transmitted difference value..
